[{"id":42007,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Excess pressure inside a soap bubble is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>T</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math>. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>T</mi></mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>T</mi></mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math></p><p>Dividing,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></mrow><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42029,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$10.5 \\mathrm{~m}$","$8.7 \\mathrm{~m}$","$11.2 \\mathrm{~m}$","$9.5 \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Using $\\mathrm{P}_1 \\mathrm{~V}_1=\\mathrm{P}_2 \\mathrm{~V}_2$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&\\left(P_1\\right) \\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3=\\left(P_2\\right) \\frac{4}{3} \\pi \\frac{125 r^3}{64} \\\\\n&\\frac{\\rho g(10)+\\rho g h}{\\rho g(10)}=\\frac{125}{64} \\\\\n&640+64 h=1250\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nOn solving we get $h=9.5 \\mathrm{~m}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":41927,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\rho \\mathrm{gh}=\\frac{4 \\mathrm{~S}}{\\mathrm{R}} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{4 \\times 0.28}{8 \\times 10^3 \\times 10 \\times 4 \\times 10^{-4}} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\frac{0.28}{8} \\mathrm{~m}=\\frac{28}{8} \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{R}=3.5 \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$\nDiameter $=7 \\mathrm{~cm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41938,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Total wing span area, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>80</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Using Bernoulli's equation, we get uplift force as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>ρ</mi><mfenced><mrow><msubsup><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>-</mo><msubsup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfenced><mi>A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mfenced><mrow><msup><mn>70</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mn>50</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><mn>80</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2400</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>40</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>9600</mn><mo> </mo><mi>kg</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42006,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math><mrow><mn>4.51</mn><mtext>&#160;gm</mtext></mrow></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>15</mn><mtext>&#160;gm</mtext></math>","<math><mrow><mn>4.15</mn><mtext>&#160;gm</mtext></mrow></math>","<math><mrow><mn>1.52</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>gm</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>mg</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>ma</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>&#960;r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi>&#961;g</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>980</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.8</mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>15</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42061,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xFIu5gTPcOKp8sf7lPnP_G4WFqOwf2iYHVdTgKvTXeE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3STe6JjGRjQhYWvyPBx5LMnFh56nMuFpHJgYxz1NA1s.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1FOZth6Zh4vqrmgGcy6Miw8nWga9UEiMA_Wg7WQ9ti8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZoQn-lAFr1DxiKZ1bb1nW1gGTaFVUQ3IsBvQ-_GJwfE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\rho_{\\text {oil }} < \\rho < \\rho_{\\text {water }}\n$$\nOil is the least dense of them so it should settle at the top with water at the base. Now the ball is denser than oil but less denser than water. So, it will sink through oil but will not sink in water. So it will stay at the oil-water interface.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":41965,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Viscous force is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>|</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>|</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>&#951;</mi><mi>A</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>025</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41939,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>v</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>v</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Ignoring buoyancy force, we can write terminal velocity as </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>π</mi><mi>η</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>v</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math> (as mass is constant)</p><p>Now, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>As</mtext><mo> </mo><mi>r</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></math></p><p>So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42048,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\theta$ increases and $h$ also increases","$\\theta$ decreases and $h$ also decreases","$\\theta$ increases and $h$ decreases","$\\theta$ decreases and $h$ increases"],"answer":2,"solution":"Angle of $\\operatorname{contact} \\theta$\n$$\n\\cos \\theta=\\frac{\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{SA}}-\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{SL}}}{\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{LA}}}\n$$\nwhen water is on a waxy or oily surface\n$\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{SA}} < \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{SL}} \\cos \\theta$ is negative i.e.,\n$$\n90^{\\circ} < \\theta < 180^{\\circ}\n$$\ni.e., angle of contact $\\theta$ increases\nAnd for $\\theta>90^{\\circ}$ liquid level in capillary\ntube fall. i.e., h decreases","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41947,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The terminal velocity is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>g</mi><mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced><mi>&#951;</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Differentiating and dividing by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></math>,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>So, the percentage error is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>T</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>As can be seen the terminal velocity is directly proportional to the square of the radius. Hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math> is false.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42053,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$a^2$","$a^3$","$a$","$a^{-1}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Terminal velocity in a viscous medium is given by:\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& V_T=\\frac{2 a^2(\\rho-\\sigma) g}{9 \\eta} \\\\\n& \\therefore V_T \\propto a^2\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":42012,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b7643273-39a1-43de-8c7c-163d9d6769fa-image.png\" /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41909,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For a thin film interference, a fringe for transmission is formed.\nWhen\n$2 \\mu x=n \\lambda$\n$\\begin{aligned} \\Rightarrow & \\frac{d x}{d t}=\\left(\\frac{d n}{d t}\\right) \\frac{\\lambda}{2 \\mu} \\\\ & =\\left(\\frac{1}{12}\\right) \\frac{560 \\times 10^{-9}}{2 \\times 1.4}=\\frac{5}{3} \\times 10^{-8} \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\\end{aligned}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & V=\\text { Volume of film }=\\pi R^2 x \\\\ & \\frac{d V}{d t}=\\pi R^2 \\frac{d x}{d t} \\\\ & =\\pi\\left(1.8 \\times 10^{-2}\\right)^2 \\frac{5}{3} \\times 10^{-8} \\mathrm{~m}^3 / \\mathrm{s} \\\\ & =54 \\pi \\times 10^{-13} \\mathrm{~m}^3 / \\mathrm{s}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41908,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$1400 \\mathrm{~cm}^3$","$600 \\mathrm{~cm}^3$","$4000 \\mathrm{~cm}^3$","$400 \\mathrm{~cm}^3$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Volume of cube inside water\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& =\\left(\\frac{\\text { Denslty of cube }}{\\text { Denslty of water }}\\right) \\times \\text { Volume of cube } \\\\\n& =\\frac{\\text { Mass of cube }}{\\text { Denslty of water }} \\\\\n& =\\frac{400 \\mathrm{gm}}{1 \\mathrm{gm} / \\mathrm{cm}^3} \\\\\n& =400 \\mathrm{~cm}^3\n\\end{aligned}$\nVolume of cube outside water\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& =\\text { Volume of cube }- \\text { Volume of cube inside water } \\\\\n& =1000 \\mathrm{~cm}^3-400 \\mathrm{~cm}^3 \\\\\n& =600 \\mathrm{~cm}^3\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41880,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$120\\sqrt{2}$","$140\\sqrt{2}$","$140\\sqrt{3}$","$120\\sqrt{3}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Volume of the cylindrical vessel, $V = 528$ dm$^3 = 528000$ cm$^3$<br><br>Radius of the vessel, $r = 40$ cm<br><br>Let the height of the vessel be $H$.<br><br>$V = \\pi r^2 H$<br><br>$528000 = \\dfrac{22}{7} \\times (40)^2 \\times H$<br><br>$H = \\dfrac{528000 \\times 7}{22 \\times 1600} = 105$ cm<br><br>The vessel is placed on a block of height equal to the vessel, so the height of the block is $105$ cm.<br><br>Depth of the hole from the top water level, $h = 70$ cm<br><br>Height of the hole from the ground, $y = \\text{Height of block} + (H - h)$<br><br>$y = 105 + (105 - 70) = 140$ cm<br><br>Velocity of efflux, $v = \\sqrt{2gh}$<br><br>Time of flight of water, $t = \\sqrt{\\dfrac{2y}{g}}$<br><br>Horizontal range, $R = v \\times t = \\sqrt{2gh} \\times \\sqrt{\\dfrac{2y}{g}} = 2\\sqrt{hy}$<br><br>$R = 2\\sqrt{70 \\times 140} = 2\\sqrt{70 \\times 70 \\times 2} = 140\\sqrt{2}$ cm<br><br>Answer: $140\\sqrt{2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42063,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\rho_3 < \\rho_1 < \\rho_2$","$\\rho_1 < \\rho_3 < \\rho_2$","$\\rho_1 < \\rho_2 < \\rho_3$","$\\rho_1 < \\rho_3 < \\rho_2$"],"answer":3,"solution":"As liquid 1 floats above liquid 2 ,\n$$\n\\rho_1 < \\rho_2\n$$\nThe ball is unable to sink into liquid 2 ,\n$\\rho_3 < \\rho_2$ The ball is unable to rise over liquid 1 ,\n$\\begin{array}{ll} & \\rho_1 < \\rho_3 \\\\ \\text { Thus, } & \\rho_1 < \\rho_3 < \\rho_2\\end{array}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":41896,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$h_{1}>h_{2} \\text { and } T_{1}=T_{2}$","$h_{1}=h_{2} \\text { and } T_{1}=T_{2}$","$h_{1} > h_{2} \\text { and } T_{1} < T_{2}$","$h_{1} < h_{2} \\text { and } T_{1}=T_{2}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For capillary rise, the height of liquid in a tube is given by: $h = \\frac{2T\\cos\\theta}{\\rho g r}$, where $T$ is surface tension and $r$ is the tube radius.<br><br>For two liquids with equal density and contact angles:<br>$h_1 = \\frac{2T_1\\cos\\theta}{\\rho g r_1}$ and $h_2 = \\frac{2T_2\\cos\\theta}{\\rho g r_2}$<br><br>Taking the ratio: $\\frac{h_1}{h_2} = \\frac{T_1}{T_2} \\times \\frac{r_2}{r_1}$<br><br>Since $r_1 > r_2$, we have $\\frac{r_2}{r_1} < 1$. The capillary rise is inversely proportional to tube radius, so the smaller radius tube will have greater height. Since the liquids are measured to have heights $h_1$ and $h_2$ with $r_1 > r_2$, and they have the same density, the empirical relation shows that both liquids rise to different heights inversely proportional to their radii. For liquids with the same density measured in different tubes, if the heights and radii satisfy the capillary rise equation, the surface tensions must be equal: $T_1 = T_2$, and $h_1 < h_2$ since $r_1 > r_2$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41949,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The formula to calculate the potential&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>V</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;of each tiny drop is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfrac><mi>q</mi><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>When all the drops forms the bigger drop the radius of the new drop&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;can be calculated as follows:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><mi>Volume</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>big</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>drop</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>volume</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>each</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>tiny</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>drop</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi><msup><mo>'</mo><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>r</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>So, the potential of the new big drop <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><mi>V</mi><mo>'</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>k</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>64</mn><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>k</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>64</mn><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>16</mn><mi>k</mi><mfrac><mi>q</mi><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Divide equation (2) by equation (1) and simplify to obtain the potential of the new drop.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><mi>k</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>q</mi><mi>r</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>q</mi><mi>r</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>V</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mi>V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Substitute the value of the known parameter into equation (3) to calculate the required value of the potential for the new drop.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><mi>V</mi><mo>'</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>160</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42064,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5ptAy2wZy80rNWn25YX50zCS6vHMk-K21-R2kb8H0os.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4Suob2J41RvR5eE2j_y9Bg7g9DHTW8zvjAIMcE4CnnU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hUgGgw5Wqj0vkoEq00LmttwMdTEQw643tABnJl5PBrA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Fi9Cd1jSEM_ml09IkV-xSVCl6pnbUdc6ZmjWjLE2Spk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Capillary rise $\\mathrm{h}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~T} \\cos \\theta}{\\rho \\mathrm{gr}}$. As soap solution has lower $\\mathrm{T}, \\mathrm{h}$ will be low.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":41893,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$+1$","-3","$+3$","-1"],"answer":0,"solution":"Capillary height formula: $h = \\frac{2\\sigma\\cos\\theta}{\\rho g r}$<br>When radius, density, and surface tension each decrease by 1%: $r' = 0.99r$, $\\rho' = 0.99\\rho$, $\\sigma' = 0.99\\sigma$<br>New height: $h' = \\frac{2(0.99\\sigma)\\cos\\theta}{(0.99\\rho) g (0.99r)} = h \\cdot \\frac{0.99}{0.99 \\times 0.99} = h \\cdot \\frac{1}{0.99} = h \\cdot 1.0101...$<br>Percentage change: $(1.0101 - 1) \\times 100 \\approx +1.01\\%$, which rounds to +1%.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41992,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>250</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>43</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>56</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>At terminal speed</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi>net</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>mg</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>&#951;</mi><mi>Rv</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>mg</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>&#951;</mi><mi>RV</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>&#951;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><mi>&#951;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>400</mn><mn>81</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42022,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Mass of liquid rising in tube <math><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">cos</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math><br />Mass of liquid rise in tube will become <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41958,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is not correct but R is correct","A is correct but R is not correct","Both A and R is correct and R is the correct explanation of A"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Pascal&#39;s law states that the pressure in a closed incompressible fluid is transmitted equally in all directions.</p><p>The formula for pressure is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>F</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>When a toothpaste is squeezed let the pressure transmitted by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math>. At the mouth of the toothpaste the pressure will also be equal to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math>&nbsp;due to Pascal&#39;s law.&nbsp;The pressure applied to the tube is transmitted equally throughout the toothpaste. When the pressure reaches the open end, it forces toothpaste out through the opening. Hence, both&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>&#38;</mo><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;is correct and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math> is correct explanation for&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41887,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let $A$ be the base area of the wooden cube.<br><br>$A = 10 \\text{ cm} \\times 10 \\text{ cm} = 100 \\text{ cm}^2$<br><br>Let $\\Delta x$ be the increase in the submerged depth of the cube when the coin is placed on it.<br><br>$\\Delta x = 3.87 \\text{ cm}$<br><br>The additional volume of water displaced due to the weight of the metal coin is $\\Delta V = A \\times \\Delta x$.<br><br>$\\Delta V = 100 \\times 3.87 = 387 \\text{ cm}^3$<br><br>By Archimedes' principle, the weight of the metal coin is balanced by the additional buoyant force, which is equal to the weight of the additional water displaced.<br><br>$m g = \\Delta V \\rho_w g$<br><br>$m = \\Delta V \\rho_w$<br><br>Substituting the values of $\\Delta V$ and the density of water $\\rho_w = 1 \\text{ g/cm}^3$:<br><br>$m = 387 \\text{ cm}^3 \\times 1 \\text{ g/cm}^3 = 387 \\text{ g}$<br><br>Answer: $387$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41970,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["Both (A) and (R) are true and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)","Both (A) and (R) are true but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A)","(A) is true but (R)&nbsp;is false","(A) is true but (R) is true"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a233dec4-53f4-41c9-be42-912329edf0d4-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 104px;\" /></p><p>Angle of contact between oil and water is obtuse i.e., greater than critical angle of contact&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>, therefore they do not stick and that&#39;s the reason grease/oil stains can not be removed by water wash.&nbsp;</p><p>Thus, both&nbsp;(A) and (R) are true and (R) is the correct explanation of (A).</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41928,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\frac{2 S}{R}$","$\\frac{4 R}{S}$","$\\frac{S}{R}$","$\\frac{4 \\mathrm{~S}}{\\mathrm{R}}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"There are two liquid-air surfaces in bubble so\n$\\Delta \\mathrm{P}=2\\left(\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~S}}{\\mathrm{R}}\\right)=\\frac{4 \\mathrm{~S}}{\\mathrm{R}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41899,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\frac{82}{5}$","$\\frac{57}{2}$","$\\frac{71}{5}$","$\\frac{68}{5}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GCimEH_kEhiHPvKs45VLTfId1mQcSQLU-kAJHRM20kk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{h}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~T} \\cos \\theta}{\\rho \\mathrm{gr}}=\\frac{2 \\times 70 \\times 1}{1 \\times 980 \\times 10^{-2}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{~h}=\\frac{100}{7} \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\ & \\sin 60^{\\circ}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\ell} \\\\ & \\ell=\\frac{\\mathrm{h} \\times 2}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ & \\ell=\\frac{100}{7} \\times \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ & =\\frac{200}{7 \\times \\sqrt{3}} \\\\ & =16.49 \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41882,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$100$ m/s","$10$ m/s","$1000$ m/s","$15 \\times 10^2$ m/s"],"answer":1,"solution":"From the equation of continuity:<br><br>$A_1 v_1 = n A_2 v_2$<br><br>Here,<br>$A_1 = 30 \\text{ cm}^2 = 30 \\times 10^{-4} \\text{ m}^2$<br>$v_1 = 50 \\text{ cm/s} = 0.5 \\text{ m/s}$<br>$n = 10$<br>$A_2 = 15 \\text{ mm}^2 = 15 \\times 10^{-6} \\text{ m}^2$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$(30 \\times 10^{-4}) \\times 0.5 = 10 \\times (15 \\times 10^{-6}) \\times v_2$<br><br>$15 \\times 10^{-4} = 150 \\times 10^{-6} \\times v_2$<br><br>$15 \\times 10^{-4} = 1.5 \\times 10^{-4} \\times v_2$<br><br>$v_2 = \\dfrac{15 \\times 10^{-4}}{1.5 \\times 10^{-4}} = 10 \\text{ m/s}$<br><br>Answer: $10$ m/s","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42046,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>22</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>38</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Using isothermal process conditions<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/23ab129a-b1d7-46fd-8fec-6dd5ed349d59-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 197px;\" /><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#8658;</mo><msub> <mi>P</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <msub> <mi>V</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mo>=</mo><msub> <mi>P</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <msub> <mi>V</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>&#8658;</mo><msub> <mi>P</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mi>A</mi><msub> <mi>&#8467;</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mo>=</mo><msub> <mi>P</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mi>A</mi><msub> <mi>&#8467;</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mn>8</mn> <mtext>p</mtext> </mrow> <msub> <mspace></mspace> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>xp</mtext> <mo>&#8658;</mo> <mtext>p</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>8</mn> <msub> <mtext>p</mtext> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>x</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(here p<sub>0</sub> = 76 cm of Hg)<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>8</mn> <msub> <mtext>p</mtext> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>x</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>&#961;</mtext> <mtext>m</mtext> </msub> <mtext>g</mtext> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>54</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>x</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> <mo>=</mo> <msub> <mtext>&#961;</mtext> <mtext>m</mtext> </msub> <mtext>g</mtext> <mtext>(76)</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>8</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>x</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>+</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>54</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>x</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>76</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math><br /><br />x = 16 cm</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":42005,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>S</mi><mfenced><mrow><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>S</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>g</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>S</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>g</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>S</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6beef5d7-07c3-40a4-a14e-cf0cd3852783-image.png\" style=\"width: 257px; height: 160px;\" /></p><p>Initial height of liquid in container&#39;s of same cross section are&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;respectively. Now value is opened find loss in potential energy when water level be become same</p><p>loss in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PE</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#961;Ax</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>&#961;A</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>&#961;Ag</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;Ag</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42039,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$4 \\mathrm{PV}+3 \\mathrm{ST}=0$","$3 \\mathrm{PV}+4 \\mathrm{ST}=0$","$2 \\mathrm{PV}+3 \\mathrm{ST}=0$","$3 \\mathrm{PV}+2 \\mathrm{ST}=0$"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42002,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#965;</mi></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#965;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#965;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#965;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>&#961;v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>&#961;V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>&#961;v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>&#961;V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42068,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["air flows from the bigger bubble to the smaller bubble till the sizes are interchanged.","air flows from bigger bubble to the smaller bubble till the sizes are interchanged","air flows from the smaller bubble to the bigger.","there is no flow of air."],"answer":2,"solution":"The pressure inside the smaller bubble will be more $\\left(P_i=P_0+\\frac{4 T}{r}\\right)$\nTherefore, if the bubbles are connected by a tube, the air will flow from smaller bubble to the bigger.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41885,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$0.88$","$8.8$","$88.8$","$0.088$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The terminal velocity of an air bubble rising in a liquid is given by Stokes' law:<br><br>$v = \\dfrac{2}{9} \\dfrac{r^2 \\rho g}{\\eta}$<br><br>Where:<br>$r = \\dfrac{D}{2} = 1 \\text{ mm} = 10^{-3} \\text{ m}$<br>$\\rho = 2000 \\text{ kg/m}^3$<br>$g = 10 \\text{ m/s}^2$<br>$v = 0.5 \\text{ cm/s} = 5 \\times 10^{-3} \\text{ m/s}$<br><br>Rearranging the formula for the coefficient of viscosity $\\eta$:<br><br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{2}{9} \\dfrac{r^2 \\rho g}{v}$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{2}{9} \\times \\dfrac{(10^{-3})^2 \\times 2000 \\times 10}{5 \\times 10^{-3}}$<br><br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{2}{9} \\times \\dfrac{10^{-6} \\times 20000}{5 \\times 10^{-3}}$<br><br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{2}{9} \\times \\dfrac{2 \\times 10^{-2}}{5 \\times 10^{-3}}$<br><br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{2}{9} \\times 4 = \\dfrac{8}{9} \\text{ Pa}\\cdot\\text{s}$<br><br>To convert the viscosity from SI units (Pa$\\cdot$s) to CGS units (Poise), we multiply by $10$:<br><br>$\\eta = \\dfrac{8}{9} \\times 10 = \\dfrac{80}{9} \\text{ Poise}$<br><br>$\\eta \\approx 8.88 \\text{ Poise}$<br><br>The closest given option is $8.8$.<br><br>Answer: $8.8$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41977,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>15</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>15</mn><msqrt><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0ab12f77-3941-45c9-98f1-363f2ff942e5-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 142px;\" /></p><p>Balancing the forces on drop&nbsp;</p><p>Buoyant force&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo></math>&nbsp;surface tension&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>mg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#963;</mi><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>RT</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>RT</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#183;</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mtext>As&#160;</mtext><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&#963;</mi></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null}]